  "text": "Focussing on the impact of profit-per-employee on wages, two models of rent-sharing through collective bargaining are commonplace. The first only assumes collective bargaining about wages at the first stage where after the firm sets employment given the wage in the second stage as, for example, in Blanchflower, Oswald & Sanfey [1996] . By contrast, [CITATION_1] model the case where there is bargaining about wages and employment. Despite the fact that both models produce the same wage equations, they are fundamentally different in that in the right-tomanage model employment is highly endogenous with regard to wages whereas in an [CITATION_2] For a discussion, see [CITATION_3] .",
